  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Commodity fetishism names the process by which commodities appear to possess inherent value, as though their price were a natural property rather than a product of human labor and social organization. Karl Marx introduced the concept in the first chapter of Capital (1867) to describe how the commodity form conceals the relations of production behind it. When a person buys a shirt, the shirt presents itself as worth a certain amount of money. The labor that produced it — the conditions, wages, coercion, skill — disappears from view.\n",
  "name": "Commodity Fetishism",
